articles.description: There are 21 five-stars in the Class of 2026. We look at how they got to their teams and what they'll do in college.

articles.headline: Jaden O'Neal gives Florida State highest-rated QB since 2022 class
articles.description: Four-star quarterback Jaden O'Neal, ranked No. 112 in the 2026 ESPN 300, announced his commitment to Florida State on Sunday night, sealing a long-anticipated flip for the former Oklahoma pledge.

articles.headline: Defensive end Richard Wesley commits to Texas Longhorns
articles.description: Defensive end Richard Wesley, a 6-foot-5, 250-pound pass rusher from Chatsworth, California, has committed to Texas, the No. 18 overall prospect in the 2026 ESPN 300 announced on Sunday night following an official visit with the Longhorns this weekend.

articles.headline: Ex-Buckeye Kirk Barton facing charge after fatal crash in Ohio
articles.description: Kirk Barton, a former captain at Ohio State who went on to play in the NFL, faces an aggravated vehicular manslaughter charge following a fatal crash early Saturday morning.

articles.headline: Notre Dame lands commitments from Khary Adams, Joey O'Brien
articles.description: Notre Dame landed pledges from a pair of top 2026 defensive back targets Friday, edging a trio of recruiting rivals to the commitments of No. 8 cornerback Khary Adams and No. 4 athlete prospect Joey O'Brien.

articles.headline: Oklahoma fills need with commitment of 4-star QB Bowe Bentley
articles.description: Four-star quarterback Bowe Bentley, No. 261 in the 2026 ESPN 300, announced his commitment to Oklahoma over LSU on Friday.

article.headline: Henigan leads Memphis over Arkansas State 44-32
article.description: — Seth Henigan threw for three touchdowns and 360 yards and Memphis survived a wild fourth quarter to edge Arkansas State 44-32 on Saturday night.
article.linkText: Henigan leads Memphis over Arkansas State 44-32

tracking.trackingName: NCF_One-Play (Joe Scates scores 51-yard receiving touchdown) 2022/09/17 ESHEET

article.story: MEMPHIS, Tenn. -- — Seth Henigan threw for three touchdowns and 360 yards and Memphis survived a wild fourth quarter to edge Arkansas State 44-32 on Saturday night. The teams combined for 38 points in the fourth quarter, with Memphis (2-1) retaking its final lead after Jevyon Ducker raced up the middle 39 yards for a 37-32 edge with just over two minutes left. The outcome was sealed after a snap got away from the Red Wolves for a 32-yard loss and a Memphis recovery at the Arkansas State 9 that led to a Brandon Thomas rushing TD. It was the Red Wolves’ first turnover this season. Chris Howard had extended a Memphis lead to 31-25 with a 47-yard field goal with nine minutes left. But Johnnie Lang found found himself wide open coming out of the backfield and James Blackman hit him for a 27-yard score and a 32-31 Red Wolves lead with 4:22 remaining. Joseph Scates completed a 51-yard pass play by spinning his way through several defenders inside the 10 and scoring to open the fourth quarter, building the Tigers' lead to 28-17. Brian Snead got the Red Wolves (1-2) within three less than two minutes later on a 7-yard run that he helped set up with a 29-yard rush. Memphis led 21-17 at halftime after Henigan's 8-yard run late in the quarter. Caden Prieskorn had two TD catches for Memphis, which outgained the Red Wolves 547-370. Blackmon threw for 275 yards and two TDs for Arkansas State. Seydou Traore had 120 yards receiving with a TD and Snead ran for two scores. Memphis won their fourth straight over Arkansas State in the teams’ 61st meeting. ------
